      "rationale": "Three mesh densities (coarse ~85k elements, medium ~210k elements, fine ~520k elements) were evaluated. Stiffness QoI changed 1.3% from medium to fine; GCI computed at 2.1%. Production mesh is medium density, providing adequate accuracy at acceptable runtime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Default Ansys sparse direct solver convergence criteria sufficient for linear-elastic regime; residual norms reported.",
      "rationale": "Analysis is quasi-static linear-elastic for stiffness QoI and mildly nonlinear for yield/post-yield QoIs. Sparse direct solver used for linear steps; Newton-Raphson with force and displacement convergence tolerances of 0.1% for nonlinear steps. Solver residual logs archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts by a second analyst not involved in model construction.",
      "rationale": "A second senior FEA engineer performed independent review of the APDL input deck, contact definitions, loading ramp, and post-processing macros. Three minor discrepancies (incorrect initial contact gap tolerance, misassigned section thickness, incorrect unit in output macro) were identified and corrected prior to final runs. Review documented in DR-FEA-2025-047."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with isotropic elastoplastic material model is an appropriate representation of titanium alloy pedicle screw behavior under quasi-static compression-bending within the F1717 load range.",
      "rationale": "Isotropic bilinear elastoplastic model (von Mises yield, isotropic hardening) is well-established for Ti-6Al-4V under monotonic quasi-static loading. Anisotropy and rate effects are negligible at F1717 test speeds. Model form uncertainty quantified via literature survey; no significant alternative model forms identified for this loading regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties, geometry, and boundary conditions traceable to measured data or authoritative sources; input uncertainty quantified.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus and yield strength sourced from Lot 22 coupon testing (Dataset material-props-ti6al4v-lot22; dataVintage 2025-08-28). Geometry from production CAD revision B. Boundary conditions replicate F1717 fixture kinematics. The September 2025 model revision updated the post-yield hardening slope from a literature value to a measured tangent modulus; the submitting team assessed this change as not material to the stiffness and yield-force QoIs, which are governed by the linear-elastic and initial-yield regime captured by the pre-revision dataset. No formal re-validation against the revised model build was conducted."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production-representative hardware; material certificates and dimensional inspection on file.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs (6 Laboratory 1, 5 Laboratory 2) assembled from production-lot screws and UHMWPE blocks per F1717. Material certificates (Ti-6Al-4V, ASTM F136) and CMM dimensional reports archived. Construct assembly performed by trained technicians per written procedure."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or sensitivity analysis demonstrates insensitivity to untested conditions.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed at a single load angle (5° compression-bending per F1717 standard). Clinical loading encompasses a range of angles and combined torsion; only the standard F1717 condition was evaluated. Sensitivity analysis to load angle not performed. This factor is below required level; risk accepted based on regulatory precedent for F1717 as a standardized worst-case condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to physical test article and test setup within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Geometric equivalency confirmed by overlay of FEA mesh with CMM point cloud (max deviation 0.08 mm). Material property inputs match coupon test mean values within measurement uncertainty. Fixture boundary conditions replicate F1717 test machine kinematics as confirmed by fixture drawing review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All three primary QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) within 10% of experimental mean and E/uval < 1.96.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: 2.8% difference, E/uval=0.91. Yield force: 2.2% difference, E/uval=0.78. Force at 40 mm: 1.6% difference, E/uval=0.63. All QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Experimental uncertainty estimated from inter-laboratory variability and instrument calibration records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness predicts load sharing with bone graft; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are standard F1717 endpoints used by FDA to characterize structural integrity. QoIs are directly relevant to the COU decision of demonstrating adequate mechanical performance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
